elements.content: Solid-state structures of cobalt(II) complexes of 4-methylumbelliferone-8-methyleneiminodiacetic acid (H3muia), also named Calcein Blue, are presented. Interestingly, ion-pair complexes with different solvation in cation, namely, [Co(H2O)4(CH3CN)2][Co(muia)(H2O)2]2 (1) and [Co(H2O)6][Co2(muia)2(H2O)2]·2CH3CN (2), exhibit self-assembly in one-pot crystallization. By variation of the experimental conditions, 1D coordination polymer [{Co(H2O)4}{Co2(muia)2(H2O)2}]·11H2O (3), which can be considered a pseudo-supramolecular isomer, is obtained. Hydrogen bonding between the cation and anion core gives an interesting hydrogen-bonded network structure. The condensation of ion-pair complexes to a 1D coordination polymer by the influence of solvents is demonstrated.

elements.content: The one-pot crystallization has successfully proven to be useful for the concomitant self-assembly of monomeric and dimeric ion-pair Co(II) complexes of Calcein Blue. The alternate arrangements of cations and anions in the 1D coordination polymer indicate that they might have formed by the condensation of these ion-pair complexes.

elements.content: The design and construction of coordination polymers are of current interest for the past two decades. Strategies for crystal engineering include the use of various intermolecular forces including hydrogen bonding. Hydrogen-bonded coordination networks exhibit interesting structural motifs and different chemical and physical properties, whereas transition metal complex ion pairs have attracted great interest because they play an important role in the chemical reactions. The substituents on the cation and anion can determine the relative anion−cation orientations, that is, the ion-pair structure, and the stoichiometry or catalytic reactivity. The ion-pair complexes can be categorized into contact ion pairs, solvent-shared ion pairs, solvent-separated ion pairs, and penetrated ion pairs. Ion-pairing and hydrogen interactions are important in the construction and design of supramolecular networks of cation and anion building blocks. Ion-pair complexes with same metal ions are also available in the literature. In some of the ion-pair complexes, the cations exist as water solvates and exhibit interesting hydrogen-bonded polymeric structures.
elements.clean_text:
Introduction

The design and construction of coordination polymers are of current interest for the past two decades. Strategies for crystal engineering include the use of various intermolecular forces including hydrogen bonding. Hydrogen-bonded coordination networks exhibit interesting structural motifs and different chemical and physical properties, whereas transition metal complex ion pairs have attracted great interest because they play an important role in the chemical reactions. The substituents on the cation and anion can determine the relative anion-cation orientations, that is, the ion-pair structure, and the stoichiometry or catalytic reactivity. The ion-pair complexes can be categorized into contact ion pairs, solvent-shared ion pairs, solvent-separated ion pairs, and penetrated ion pairs. Ion-pairing and hydrogen interactions are important in the construction and design of supramolecular networks of cation and anion building blocks. Ion-pair complexes with same metal ions are also available in the literature. In some of the ion-pair complexes, the cations exist as water solvates and exhibit interesting hydrogen-bonded polymeric structures.

elements.content: In the process of exploring the multidentate ligands that contain various hydrogen-bonding functionalities, we have chosen a readily available multidentate ligand, 4-methylumbelliferone-8-methyleneiminodiacetic acid (H3muia). This tetradentate ligand was prepared by Wilkins and Eggers independently and later was assigned the commercial name of Calcein Blue, which has proven to be useful as an indicator in the EDTA titration of calcium and some transition metals. In addition, it shows strong fluorescence in the presence of the alkaline earth metals and is quenched by the transition metals. Its synthetic procedure, absorption, and fluorescence properties as functions of pH and the nature of the reaction with alkaline earth metals are well established. However, this multidentate ligand containing aminocarboxylate groups with a coumarin skeleton, which contains various functional supramolecular synthons, has never been studied for its coordination behavior in the solid state. Furthermore, despite that Calcein Blue has been used for determination of metals, there is no report on the structures of metal complexes in the solid state. In this paper, we report for the first time synthesis, characterization and crystal structures of cobalt(II) complexes of the muia anion.

elements.content: General Considerations. All starting materials were obtained commercially (Calcein Blue from Sigma and Co(CH3COO)2·4H2O from Riedel de Haen) and used as received. The elemental analyses were performed in the microanalytical laboratory, Department of Chemistry, National University of Singapore. The infrared spectra (KBr pellet) were recorded using an FTS165 Bio-Rad FTIR spectrophotometer in the range of 400−4000 cm-1. ESI mass spectra were recorded on a Finnigan MAT LCQ mass spectrometer using the syringe pump method. Solvent present in the compounds was determined using an SDT 2960 TGA thermal analyzer with a heating rate of 5 °C min-1 from room temperature to 600 °C. The electronic transmittance spectral data were recorded on a Shimadzu UV-2501 PC UV−vis spectrophotometer in the wavelength of 300−800 nm using Nujol mulls and in MeOH solution. The d−d transition for all complexes is much weaker compared with the ligand to metal charge transfer (LMCT) band and thus was determined with higher concentration.

Experimental Section

 General Considerations. All starting materials were obtained commercially (Calcein Blue from Sigma and Co(CH3COO)2⋅4H2O from Riedel de Haen) and used as received. The elemental analyses were performed in the microanalytical laboratory, Department of Chemistry, National University of Singapore. The infrared spectra (KBr pellet) were recorded using an FTS165 Bio-Rad FTIR spectrophotometer in the range of 400-4000 cm-1. ESI mass spectra were recorded on a Finnigan MAT LCQ mass spectrometer using the syringe pump method. Solvent present in the compounds was determined using an SDT 2960 TGA thermal analyzer with a heating rate of 5 °C min-1 from room temperature to 600 °C. The electronic transmittance spectral data were recorded on a Shimadzu UV-2501 PC UV-vis spectrophotometer in the wavelength of 300-800 nm using Nujol mulls and in MeOH solution. The d-d transition for all complexes is much weaker compared with the ligand to metal charge transfer (LMCT) band and thus was determined with higher concentration.

elements.content: Synthesis of [Co(H 2 O) 4 (CH 3 CN) 2 ][Co(muia)(H 2 O) 2 ] 2 , 1. To H3muia (64 mg, 0.2 mmol) in 0.1 M KOH (4 mL), Co(CH3COO)2·4H2O (50 mg, 0.2 mmol) in MeOH (2 mL) was added and stirred for 15 min. Acetonitrile (15 mL) was layered on the resulting orange clear solution. Orange rod crystals were obtained after 1 week. Alternatively, single crystals of 1 can be obtained as a single product when acetonitrile is layered as a buffer layer between the solution of H3muia and Co(CH3COO)2·4H2O. Compound 1 loses solvent upon decantion from the mother liquor. Elemental analysis and TGA analysis was done on the air-dried sample, and it was found that one acetonitrile solvent molecule is lost during the analysis. Yield:  25 mg (69%). ESI-MS 377.3 [CoC15H12NO7]-. Anal. Calcd. for dehydrated compound C32H43N3O22Co3:  C, 38.49; H, 4.34; N, 4.21. Found:  C, 38.47; H, 4.37; N, 4.95. IR (KBr, cm-1):  υ(free OH) 3527; υ(OH) 3308; υas (COO - ) 1685; υas (COO - ) 1587; υs (COO - ) 1388. Calcd. TG weight loss of dehydrated compound 18.5%; found 18.9%. elements.content: X-ray Crystallography. The diffraction experiments were carried out on a Bruker AXS SMART CCD diffractometer with Mo Kα (λ = 0.71073 Å) in a sealed tube. The program SMART was used for collecting frames of data, indexing reflections, and determining lattice parameters; SAINT was used for integration of the intensity of reflections and scaling; SADABS was used for absorption correction; and SHELXTL was used for space group and structure determination and least-squares refinements on F 2. All the non-hydrogen atoms were refined anisotropically. All the C−H hydrogen atoms were placed in calculated positions. All the hydrogen atoms of solvent molecules in 1 and 2 were located, and their positional parameters were refined in the least-squares refinements. Eleven lattice water molecules in 3 (O13 to O22) were found to be disordered. Common thermal parameters were refined for all the disordered O atoms. The disordered positions of the O13 water molecule were resolved with occupancy of 0.5 each, whereas the occupancies of other O atoms of the lattice water molecules vary from 0.2 to 0.5. No hydrogen atom was added to these water molecules. Crystallographic details for 1 − 3 are given in Table .

Reaction of H3muia ligand with Co(CH3COO)2·4H2O in an equimolar ratio gave rod-like orange crystals of [Co(H2O)4(CH3CN)2][Co(muia)(H2O)2]2 (1) when layered with excess acetonitrile after 1 week. Single-crystal X-ray diffraction reveals that 1, crystallized in the triclinic space group P1̄, is an ion-pair complex. Interestingly, red cubic crystals of [Co(H2O)6][Co2(muia)2(H2O)2]·2CH3CN (2), crystallized in the monoclinic space group P21/c, can be obtained as a minor product from the same mother liquor after the evaporation of acetonitrile solvent.

Results and Discussion

Reaction of H3muia ligand with Co(CH3COO)2⋅4H2O in an equimolar ratio gave rod-like orange crystals of [Co(H2O)4(CH3CN)2][Co(muia)(H2O)2]2 (1) when layered with excess acetonitrile after 1 week. Single-crystal X-ray diffraction reveals that 1, crystallized in the triclinic space group P1̄, is an ion-pair complex. Interestingly, red cubic crystals of [Co(H2O)6][Co2(muia)2(H2O)2]⋅2CH3CN (2), crystallized in the monoclinic space group P21/c, can be obtained as a minor product from the same mother liquor after the evaporation of acetonitrile solvent.

elements.content: A ball and stick diagram of 1 is shown in Figure . Compound 1 is an ion-pair complex that consists of solvated cobalt cation and two complex anions. In the anionic unit, the muia ligand is coordinated to the Co(II) center, which adopts a distorted octahedral geometry, comprised of a tertiary amine N (Co(1)−N(1), 2.140(2) Å), phenolic O (Co(1)−O(1), 2.040(2) Å), two carboxylate O (Co(1)−O(2), 2.115(2)Å and Co(1)−O(4), 2.077(2) Å), and two aqua ligands (Co(1)−O(8), 2.134(2) Å, Co(1)−O(9), 2.085(2) Å). As for the cation, four water molecules and two acetonitrile are coordinated to the Co(II) center.

elements.content: [Co(H2O)6][Co2(muia)2(H2O)2]·2CH3CN (2), obtained from the same reaction mixture after a longer crystallization period, is a minor product. A perspective view of 2 is shown in Figure . In the dimeric structure, a tertiary amine N (Co(1)−N(1), 2.157(2) Å), two bridging phenolic O (Co(1)−O(1), 2.116(2) Å and Co(1)-O(1a), 2.054(2) Å), two carboxylate O (Co(1)−O(2), 2.111(2) Å and Co(1)−O(4), 2.082(2) Å) and an aqua ligand (Co(1)−O(8), 2.127(2) Å) are coordinated to each Co(II) center. The phenolic oxygen, O(1), bridged to another Co(II) center to form a Co2O2 ring, the center of which serves as inversion center.

elements.content: Interestingly, each unit of the dinuclear complex has two negative charges neutralized by a neighboring hydrated cation, [Co(H2O)6]2+, which is hydrogen bonded to two dimeric anions as shown in Figure a. The carboxylate groups of the anionic dimers are hydrogen bonded to the aqua ligands of the hexaaquacobalt cation resulting in the arrangement of alternate cation and anion units in two dimensions. The details of the packing in different direction are displayed in Figure b. Table contains some of the selected hydrogen bond parameters of 2. The neighboring aromatic rings are arranged parallel to each other to form a 1D hydrogen-bonded polymer along the a-axis as shown in Figure b, but the rings are slip-stacked such that the O6 atom falls at the center of the phenyl ring of the neighboring anion with the distance of 3.436 Å. Other closer distances between the aromatic rings are 3.451 Å between C1 and C12 and 3.318 Å between C5 atoms. Such π−π stacking in metal complexes with aromatic rings is important in stabilizing the supramolecular structures in the solid state. In short, 2 is an interesting ion-pair complex in which the water molecules and muia ligands interpose between the ions. Six coordinated water molecules on the Co(2) act as solvent, which separated the ions and sustained the hydrogen-bonded network.

elements.content: In this context, compounds 1 and 2 are one-pot crystallized compounds of which 1 is a kinetic product in the presence of excess acetonitrile solvent, whereas a longer period of crystallization allows evaporation of acetonitrile and facilitates the formation of 2. In 1, the Co(2) atom is solvated by water and acetonitrile molecules. When the monomeric anion dimerized by bridging through phenolic oxygen, the acetonitrile molecules of the Co(2) atom were replaced by water molecules and a stable hexaaquacation was formed. The concentration of acetonitrile plays an important role in the formation of monomeric and dimeric structure as well as the type of ion pair of cobalt(II) complexes. The hydrogen bonding and π−π interactions are responsible for the structural and conformational changes from 1 to 2.

elements.content: The 1D coordination polymer strands further interact with neighboring strands and water molecules to furnish a 2D network sustained by the hydrogen bonding as depicted in Figure . The packing diagram of 3 reveals that a (H2O)16 water cluster may be encapsulated within the crystal lattice between the two strands of 1D polymer. However, the exact nature of this water cluster is not very well-defined due to partial occupancy and disorder present in the lattice water oxygen atoms. It is worth noting that the water cluster shows a chairlike conformation consisting of four lattice water molecules and two aqua ligands, which are bonded to Co(2) atom. Chairlike cyclic hexamer water clusters have been reported theoretically and experimentally.

elements.content: Compounds 2 and 3 are pseudo-supramolecular isomers which differ in the nature of the solvent molecules. The major difference between 2 and 3 lies on the hydrated Co(2) atom. In 3, only four water molecules are bonded to the Co(2) atom, and the octahedral geometry is completed by two carbonyl O atoms from the neighboring dinuclear unit, whereas in 2, the Co(2) atom is coordinated with two more water molecules to form a stable hexaaquacobalt cation.

elements.content: In summary, this report presents interesting solid-state structures of metal complexes of Calcein Blue. The one-pot crystallization has successfully proven to be useful for the concomitant self-assembly of monomeric and dimeric ion-pair cobalt complexes. In all these compounds, the hydrated or solvated cobalt moieties are involved and stabilized the formation of a hydrogen-bonded network. The isolation of structures of these ion-pair complexes appears to indicate the role played by the solvents in the condensation of simple ion-pair complexes to neutral 1D coordination polymers.
elements.clean_text:
Conclusion

In summary, this report presents interesting solid-state structures of metal complexes of Calcein Blue. The one-pot crystallization has successfully proven to be useful for the concomitant self-assembly of monomeric and dimeric ion-pair cobalt complexes. In all these compounds, the hydrated or solvated cobalt moieties are involved and stabilized the formation of a hydrogen-bonded network. The isolation of structures of these ion-pair complexes appears to indicate the role played by the solvents in the condensation of simple ion-pair complexes to neutral 1D coordination polymers.

Synthesis of [Co(H 2 O) 4 (CH 3 CN) 2 ][Co(muia)(H 2 O) 2 ] 2 , 1. To H3muia (64 mg, 0.2 mmol) in 0.1 M KOH (4 mL), Co(CH3COO)2·4H2O (50 mg, 0.2 mmol) in MeOH (2 mL) was added and stirred for 15 min. Acetonitrile (15 mL) was layered on the resulting orange clear solution. Orange rod crystals were obtained after 1 week. Alternatively, single crystals of 1 can be obtained as a single product when acetonitrile is layered as a buffer layer between the solution of H3muia and Co(CH3COO)2·4H2O. Compound 1 loses solvent upon decantion from the mother liquor. Elemental analysis and TGA analysis was done on the air-dried sample, and it was found that one acetonitrile solvent molecule is lost during the analysis. Yield:  25 mg (69%). ESI-MS 377.3 [CoC15H12NO7]-. Anal. Calcd. for dehydrated compound C32H43N3O22Co3:  C, 38.49; H, 4.34; N, 4.21. Found:  C, 38.47; H, 4.37; N, 4.95. IR (KBr, cm-1):  υ(free OH) 3527; υ(OH) 3308; υas (COO - ) 1685; υas (COO - ) 1587; υs (COO - ) 1388. Calcd. TG weight loss of dehydrated compound 18.5%; found 18.9%. UV−vis (λmax (nm), ε (M-1 cm-1)):  (methanol) LMCT, 353(5680), d−d transition, 518(140); (nujol mull) LMCT, 370 nm.

Synthesis of [Co(H 2 O) 6 ][Co 2 (muia) 2 (H 2 O) 2 ]·2CH 3 CN, 2. When the above solution was left for 2 weeks, red cubic crystals of 2 were obtained. Yield:  8 mg (4%). ESI-MS 377.1 [CoC15H12NO7]-. Orange block crystals were obtained after 5 days. Yield:  64 mg (17%). ESI-MS 377.2 [CoC15H12NO7]-. Anal. Calcd. for C30H40N2O22Co3:  C, 37.63; H, 4.21; N, 2.93. Found:  C, 37.57; H, 4.17; N, 2.90.
